Baltimore’s
- Development





Program



1988-

Baltimore’s Development Program: 1988-1993 is
the timetable of construction that the City plans to
implement during the next six years. The first year
of this six-year program has been adopted by the
City Council as Baltimore’s Capital Budget.

The 1988-1993 Capital Improvement Program is
comprised of projects totalling $1.52 billion. This
funding is allocated between the following
categories:

® $27 million for recreation and park facilities.

® $326 million for housing and community
development

® $116 million for education projects

® $369 million for street, bridge and highway
projects

® $299 million for waste water construction
projects

® $104 million for improvements to the water
supply system

® $279 million for other projects (libraries, Jail and
Health facilities, parking, Markets, Police, Fire,
Museums and storm water projects and the
Aquarium, Convention Center and Baltimore
Arena.

The level of expenditures alone suggests the
magnitude of the impact that this Development
Program will have on the fabric of the City.

Underlying the 1988-1993 Development
Program is the basic idea that in addition to
providing necessary public facilities, City
expenditures must be used to stimulate private
investment in Baltimore.

Only in this way will the City be able to realize
the goals, policies, and programs mapped in the
City’s long-range plans and increase the variety
and strength of all urban resources, to serve all
the citizens of Baltimore.
